# Development Lifecycle

## Stages

```
IDEA → DRAFT → REFINE → IMPLEMENT → PR → (RELEASE)
```

### Draft
A raw idea or bug report added with `/draft`. No planning required.
Spec file created in `docs/specs/backlog/`. Minimal content — just enough to capture the idea.

### Refine
A Requirements Engineer and Tech Planner iterate on the draft until it meets the **Definition of Ready**.
Triggered with `/refine {id}`. The user can choose autonomy level (fully-autonomous / key-questions-only / many-questions).
Spec moves to `docs/specs/ready/` when DoR is satisfied.

### Implement
Tests are written first (isolated context, spec-only), then code is implemented subtask by subtask.
Each subtask gets its own commit. Run with `/implement {id}`.
Progress is checkpointed — use `/resume` after any interruption.

### PR
CI runs first (lint + typecheck + tests + security). Claude waits for CI, then runs code review,
security review, and optionally architect review. All findings are fixed before merge.
Run with `/pr`. Claude auto-merges after all reviews pass.

### Release
Version bump, CHANGELOG update, git tag, push. CI publishes the release.
Run with `/release patch|minor|major`.

---

## Context Management

Long sessions (especially `/implement` on a non-trivial feature) can approach the context limit. Compress proactively rather than reactively.

**When to run `/compact`:**
- After each subtask's commit — right before starting the next one
- After a `/pr` review-and-fix cycle closes
- After `/refine` finishes (before `/implement` begins)
- Whenever the conversation exceeds ~40 messages

**Before every compact:**
1. Commit and push all in-progress changes
2. Update `.claude/memory/context.md` (task ID, branch, next step)
3. Confirm spec checkboxes reflect actual progress

After compacting, read `.claude/memory/context.md` to re-orient before continuing.

